I say this to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I travel often abroad and my foreign friends ask me every time, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is happening in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
Firstly, be careful not to misunderstand the 2016 elections.
Unlike some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet, Trump failed to win the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand more votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
Cela dit, the victory of Trump raises the real issue of the rise of social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the vast difference between California and the Appalachians.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among White individuals with low incomes without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically were at the bottom of inequalities.
In 1999, the mortality rates among Whites without higher education were around 30% below those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
In addition, employment in manufacturing, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class Whites, has sharply declined over the last generation, making up only 2% of the workforce.
<s>Ces anciens électeurs démocrates ont été séduits par les promesses de Trump de faire bouger les choses et de ramener des emplois dans l'industrie.
<s>Paradoxalement, les efforts de Trump pour abroger la législation du Président Barack Obama en matière de soins de santé risquent bien de leur rendre la vie encore plus dure.
<s>La deuxième chose que je dis à mes amis étrangers, c'est qu'il ne faut pas sous-estimer les talents de communication de Trump.
<s>De nombreuses personnes sont choquées par ses colères sur Twitter et par son mépris scandaleux envers les faits.
<s>Mais Trump est un vétéran de la télé-réalité, où il a appris que la clé du succès consiste à monopoliser l'attention des téléspectateurs, et que la meilleure façon d'y parvenir consiste à formuler des déclarations extrêmes, sans se soucier de la vérité.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his never-ending self-centered campaign to actual governing attempts, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who loses the popular vote tends to move toward the political center to gain more support.
C'st ce que George W. Bush a fait avec succès en 2001.
Trump, en revanche, proclame qu'il a remporté le vote populaire et en agissant comme si cela était vraiment le cas, plaît à ses électeurs de base.
Bien que Trump ait fait de solides nominations centristes au Département de la Défense, d'État et la Sécurité nationale, son choix pour l'Agence de Protection de l'Environnement et pour le ministère de la Santé et des Services aux personnes se situent aux extrêmes du Parti républicain.
Son personnel à la Maison Blanche est divisé entre des idéologues et des pragmatiques - et il entend satisfaire les deux camps à la fois.
Quatrièmement, il ne faut pas sous-estimer les institutions américaines.
<s>Parfois mes amis parlent comme si le ciel leur tombait sur la tête et me demandent si Trump est un narcissique aussi dangereux que Mussolini.
<s>Je leur dis de ne pas paniquer.
<s>Les États-Unis, malgré leurs nombreux problèmes, ne sont pas l'Italie de 1922.
<s>Nos élites politiques nationales sont souvent polarisées ; mais les fondateurs de l'Amérique l'étaient tout autant.
<s>Dans la conception de la Constitution des États-Unis, l'objectif des fondateurs n'était pas de s'assurer que le gouvernement soit harmonieux, mais de limiter le pouvoir politique à un système d'équilibre des pouvoirs qui rende difficile l'exercice de ces pouvoirs.
<s>A joke about this says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us — impossible for him or anyone else.
<s>Inefficiency has been put in service of liberty.
<s>Trump's presidency is still in its early days and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
<s>However, thus far, the courts, Congress, and the states have watched over this balance of powers within the administration, according to Madison's wishes.
<s>And permanent executive branch officials still carry weight.
<s>Finally, my friends wonder what all of this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
<s>Honestly, I do not know, but I am less worried about the rise of China than about that of Trump.
<s>Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
<s>Despite the problems of the international order under US leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
<s>But no one can assert with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational problems.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his administration suggest that he may persist.
After all, the power to constrain and the power to convince the United States comes largely from having 60 allies (whereas China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's commons, is more uncertain.
<s>The Trump Budget Director talks about a budget of constraint, with cuts to the State Department and the UN system.
<s>Other government members argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements.
<s>I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them on these issues.
<s>But I can't.
